renigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1210–1245":"1210–1245","1217–1257":"1217–1257","1240–1300":"1240–1300","1170–1257":"1170–1257","1176–1215":"1176–1215","1217":"1217","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1257":"1257","1245":"1245","1300":"1300","1210":"1210","1176":"1176","1230":"1230","1197":"1197","1240":"1240","1170":"1170","Spilsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Spilsby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Willoughby, Lincolnshire, England":"Willoughby, Lincolnshire, England","Orby, Lincolnshire, England":"Orby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Orreby","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Urry  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Urry","meanings":["English: variant of   Urey  ."]},{"name":"Orry","meanings":["English: variant of   Orrey  ;  see  Urry  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":5,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":14,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Orreby was born in 1210, in Orby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, John de Orreby, was 41 and her mother, Isabel de Alfreton, was 35. She married Robert de Willoughby in 1230, in Willoughby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1245, in Willoughby, Lincolnshire, England, at the age of 35."},"et":{"1210–1245":"1210–1245","1217–1257":"1217–1257","1240–1300":"1240–1300","1170–1257":"1170–1257","1176–1215":"1176–1215","1217":"1217","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1257":"1257","1245":"1245","1300":"1300","1210":"1210","1176":"1176","1230":"1230","1197":"1197","1240":"1240","1170":"1170","Spilsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Spilsby, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Willoughby, Lincolnshire, England":"Willoughby, Lincolnshire, England","Orby, Lincolnshire, England":"Orby, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1210–1245":"1210–1245","1217–1257":"1217–1257","1240–1300":"1240–1300","1170–1257":"1170–1257","1176–1215":"1176–1215","1217":"1217","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1257":"1257","1245":"1245","1300":"1300","1210":"1210","1176":"1176","1230":"1230","1197":"1197","1240":"1240","1170":"1170","Spilsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Spilsby, Lincolnshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Willoughby, Lincolnshire, England":"Willoughby, Lincolnshire, England","Orby, Lincolnshire, England":"Orby, Lincolnshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1210–1245":"1210–1245","1217–1257":"1217–1257","1240–1300":"1240–1300","1170–1257":"1170–1257","1176–1215":"1176–1215","1217":"1217","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1257":"1257","1245":"1245","1300":"1300","1210":"1210","1176":"1176","1230":"1230","1197":"1197","1240":"1240","1170":"1170","Spilsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Spilsby, Lincolnshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Willough